exploit_payload.code_snippet:
// A malicious pod serves a tar archive with traversal entries.
// The attacker controls the pod or its responses.
// When the client calls copyDirectoryFromPod(namespace, pod, container, "/tmp/data", Paths.get("/tmp/dest")),
// the pod's tar command returns an archive where entry names include traversal sequences.
// Simulated malicious archive entry:
// TarArchiveEntry entry = new TarArchiveEntry("../../../../etc/cron.d/evil");
// This results in: new File("/tmp/dest", "../../../../etc/cron.d/evil")
// which resolves to /etc/cron.d/evil
// The attacker writes a cron job to achieve code execution on the client machine.

// Concrete scenario:
// 1. Attacker controls a pod in the cluster (or compromises one)
// 2. Client calls: copy.copyDirectoryFromPod(ns, pod, null, "/tmp/data", Paths.get("/safe/dest"))
// 3. Pod returns a crafted tar with entry '../../../etc/cron.d/backdoor'
// 4. copyDirectoryFromPod writes the attacker's content to /etc/cron.d/backdoor
// 5. Cron executes attacker's commands as root

